Note: ============================================================================
Note: COBOL Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The COBOL lexer carries both the cursor state (position/line/column/current_char)
and a fixed_format flag because COBOL's column-sensitive grammar (cols 1-6 sequence,
col 7 indicator, cols 8-72 code) is part of lexing, not parsing. The arena pointer
is held so every lexeme can be cut from arena memory without touching the heap.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
A 64-byte record (8 x i64 slots) addressing source pointer, byte position, total
length, 1-based line, 1-based column, current_char (or -1 for EOF), arena handle,
and fixed_format mode. Field offsets are 0/8/16/24/32/40/48/56 and are accessed
via Layout.memory_get_int64/memory_set_int64 across the lexer routines.
@End Implementation

Type called "COBOLLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    position as Integer         Note: Current position in source
    length as Integer           Note: Source code length
    line as Integer             Note: Current line number
    column as Integer           Note: Current column number
    current_char as Integer     Note: Current character
    arena as Integer            Note: Arena for token lexemes
    fixed_format as Integer     Note: 1 if fixed-format, 0 if free-format
End Type

@Reasoning:
Tokens are emitted as 32-byte records so the parser sees a uniform value per
position. Lexeme storage is intentionally indirect (a pointer into arena
memory) so identifier/literal text outlives token construction without copies.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots at offsets 0/8/16/24: token type constant, lexeme pointer
(arena-allocated string), source line, source column. EOF/error tokens carry
lexeme = 0.
@End Implementation

Type called "COBOLToken":
    type as Integer             Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer           Note: Token text (arena-allocated)
    line as Integer             Note: Line number
    column as Integer           Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL uniquely supports two source layouts: fixed-format (the historical
mainframe layout with cols 1-6 = sequence number, col 7 = indicator,
cols 8-72 = code area A/B, cols 73-80 = identification) and free-format
(modern, column-irrelevant). The lexer must know the mode at construction
because tokenisation differs at the column-7 indicator (`*` = comment
line, `-` = continuation, `D` = debug, space = normal). We auto-detect by
sampling indicator columns from the first ten lines - heuristic, but
robust because any modern free-format file lacks the column-7 dense
indicator pattern that fixed-format ALWAYS exhibits. The arena handle
is stored once so every token's lexeme allocation comes out of the same
pool, freeing in O(1) at end-of-compilation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 64-byte lexer record (8 slots * 8 bytes) via Layout.allocate;
returns 0 on failure. Reads source_len via StringCore.string_length.
Writes: 0=source ptr, 8=position=0, 16=source_len, 24=line=1, 32=column=1,
48=arena. Calls detect_fixed_format(source, source_len) and stores the
0/1 result at offset 56. If source_len > 0, reads the first byte via
string_char_at(source, 0) and writes it at offset 40 (current_char);
empty sources write 0 at offset 40 (immediate-EOF state).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_cobol_lexer" takes source as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create COBOL lexer from source code

    Let lexer_size be 64  Note: 8 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0         Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1        Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1        Note: column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, arena

    Note: Detect fixed-format COBOL (default to free-format)
    Let is_fixed be proc detect_fixed_format with source, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, is_fixed

    If source_len is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, first_char

    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
    End If

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Format detection is heuristic-based because fixed and free formats share
the same lexical alphabet - we can only distinguish by COLUMN PATTERNS,
specifically the column-7 indicator zone. A fixed-format source almost
always has at least a few `*` (comment) lines in the first dozen lines.
We sample up to 10 lines and require 3+ column-7 indicators (`*` or `-`)
to declare fixed format. Sources shorter than 72 characters cannot
possibly be fixed-format (cols 73-80 are mandatory in that layout)
so we early-out to free-format. False negatives (treating fixed as free)
break tokenisation; false positives (treating free as fixed) just enforce
unused column constraints, which is safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 if length < 72 (too short to be fixed). Initialises
lines_checked=0, fixed_indicators=0, pos=0. Outer loop: if
lines_checked >= 10, returns 1 when indicators > 3 else 0. Reads
col7_pos = pos + 6 (0-indexed column 7); if in-range, reads the byte;
if it equals 42 ('*') or 45 ('-'), bumps fixed_indicators. Inner loop
walks forward until newline (10) is consumed, bumping lines_checked.
After the outer loop falls through (EOF before 10 lines), returns 1
when indicators > 2, else 0 (looser threshold for short files).
@End Implementation

Process called "detect_fixed_format" takes source as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Detect if COBOL source is fixed-format

    If length is less than 72:
        Return 0  Note: Too short for fixed-format
    End If

    Let lines_checked be 0
    Let fixed_indicators be 0
    Let pos be 0

    While pos is less than length:
        If lines_checked is greater than or equal to 10:
            Note: Checked enough lines
            If fixed_indicators is greater than 3:
                Return 1
            End If
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Check column 7 (position 6) for indicator
        Let col7_pos be pos plus 6
        If col7_pos is less than length:
            Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, col7_pos
            If char is equal to 42:  Note: '*' comment indicator
                Set fixed_indicators to fixed_indicators plus 1
            End If
            If char is equal to 45:  Note: '-' continuation indicator
                Set fixed_indicators to fixed_indicators plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Note: Skip to next line
        While pos is less than length:
            Let c be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, pos
            Set pos to pos plus 1
            If c is equal to 10:  Note: newline
                Set lines_checked to lines_checked plus 1
                Note: Break out of inner loop
                Set pos to pos plus 0
                If pos is greater than 0:
                    Note: Continue outer loop
                End If
            End If
        End While
    End While

    If fixed_indicators is greater than 2:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer record itself is the only thing this function frees. Token
lexemes (the variable-length identifier/literal text) all live in the
arena that the caller passed at construction - freeing the arena (which
the CALLER does at end-of-translation-unit) frees every lexeme in O(1).
Idempotent on null lexer so callers can free unconditionally without
needing a flag to track whether construction succeeded.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If lexer is non-zero, calls Layout.deallocate to release the 64-byte
record. Always returns 1. No iteration over tokens - they're not stored
in the lexer (it produces them on demand via next_token); each token
the caller still holds is the caller's responsibility, or lives in
the arena.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_cobol_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy COBOL lexer

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The lexer's per-character workhorse. Maintains 1-based line/column
tracking so any token created downstream carries the source coordinates
used in error messages. Newlines reset column to 1 and bump line - we
intentionally process the newline AFTER reading it (newline IS column 1
of the next line in our model), which matches how most editors number
positions. Column tracking is critical for fixed-format mode where
indicator-column detection needs the running column to know when we're
in cols 1-6 (sequence), col 7 (indicator), or cols 8-72 (code).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8), length (offset 16), current_char (offset 40).
If current_char equals 10 (newline): reads line at offset 24, writes
line+1, and resets column at offset 32 to 1. Otherwise reads column and
writes column+1. Bumps position by 1 and persists at offset 8. If new
position < length, reads next_char via string_char_at and writes it at
offset 40; otherwise writes 0 (EOF sentinel) at offset 40. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Move to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1

    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column plus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    If position is less than length:
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Let next_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, next_char

    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constant-time lookahead without mutating the lexer state. The parameter
is an OFFSET (0 = current, 1 = next, 2 = the one after, ...) rather than
absolute position - this matches how the COBOL token scanners want to
ask "what's the character after this one?" Out-of-range peeks return 0
(the EOF sentinel), letting callers treat peek-past-EOF uniformly with
peek-at-EOF without special-casing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8) and length (offset 16). Computes
peek_pos = position + offset. If peek_pos >= length returns 0 (EOF).
Otherwise reads source pointer (offset 0) and returns
string_char_at(source, peek_pos). Pure read - the lexer state is
untouched.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look ahead at character at offset

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inlined ASCII range test rather than a stdlib call so the scanner's tight
character-dispatch loop stays branch-predictable and free of cross-module
indirection. COBOL number literals (PIC 9, level numbers, picture counts)
hit this on every column, so it must remain a leaf function with no
allocation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two nested range comparisons against the ASCII codepoints 48 ('0') and 57
('9'). Returns 1 only when both bounds are satisfied; falls through to 0
otherwise. The nested form (rather than a single boolean and) matches the
shape required by Runa's emitted code path which compiles each comparison
independently.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit (0-9)

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85's identifier alphabet is strict: A-Z, a-z, digits (in non-leading
position), and hyphen. Underscore is NOT in standard COBOL - some
extensions allow it but bootstrap COBOL targets the standard. We separate
is_alpha from is_alphanumeric so the leading-character test (which forbids
digits and hyphens) can reuse just is_alpha while the body test (which
allows both) uses is_alphanumeric. The two ASCII ranges (uppercase 65-90,
lowercase 97-122) are tested independently rather than combined into a
single boolean to match Runa's nested-If codegen idiom.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two nested range tests. First: if char >= 65 and char <= 90 (A..Z),
returns 1. Second: if char >= 97 and char <= 122 (a..z), returns 1.
Falls through to Return 0. Pure function - no lexer state touched.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The continuation-character test for COBOL identifier scanning. After a
leading is_alpha character, any subsequent character that's alphanumeric
OR a hyphen continues the identifier. Hyphen-in-identifier is one of
COBOL's most distinctive features (e.g., `MAIN-PROGRAM`, `EMPLOYEE-NUMBER`)
and forces a token-scanner design that cannot use simple is_alnum tests
- we explicitly include codepoint 45. We do NOT include underscore here
because COBOL-85 forbids it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
First tests via is_digit; on match returns 1. Then tests via is_alpha;
on match returns 1. Final test: if char == 45 (hyphen), returns 1.
Otherwise returns 0. The ordering (digit/alpha/hyphen) is mildly
optimized for hot identifier scanning - digits and alphas dominate the
character mix; hyphens are rarer.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric or hyphen

    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit from char
    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 45:  Note: hyphen
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Only the three whitespace codepoints the COBOL fixed-format lexer actually
consumes are tested here. Form-feed and vertical tab are excluded
deliberately because COBOL-85 column layout (cols 1-6 sequence, 7 indicator,
8-72 area A/B) treats them as data, not separators, so accepting them here
would corrupt continuation-line handling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three independent equality tests against ASCII 32 (space), 9 (tab), and 10
(newline). Each match returns 1 immediately; falls through to 0 (CR is
checked in the calling site of the line-end logic, not here, to keep this
helper aligned with what the column tracker considers a horizontal
separator).
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comment Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL is whitespace-tolerant - any number of spaces, tabs, newlines, or
carriage returns can appear between tokens (in both fixed and free
formats). Fixed-format does have column-specific rules but those are
applied by the higher-level next_token dispatcher when it encounters
the start of a new line; once we know we're scanning whitespace WITHIN
a line, all four whitespace codepoints are skippable. EOF (current_char
== 0) breaks the loop immediately so we don't advance past end of
source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_char (offset 40). Loop: when current_char == 0 (EOF) exit.
Calls is_whitespace(current_char); if returns 0 (non-whitespace), the
function returns 1 immediately. Otherwise calls advance(lexer) and
refreshes current_char from offset 40. Each iteration consumes exactly
one whitespace byte and re-tests. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While current_char is not equal to 0:
        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace from current_char
        If is_ws is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL comments are line-rest comments in both formats but with different
introducers: fixed-format uses `*` in col 7 (the whole line is a
comment), free-format and inline use `*>`. From this procedure's
viewpoint the introducer has already been consumed by the caller; our
job is simply "advance past everything up to and including the next
newline". This makes the procedure symmetric for both comment styles
and reduces dispatcher complexity in next_token.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_char from offset 40. Loop while current_char != 0 (EOF):
if it equals 10 (newline), calls advance to consume the newline and
returns 1. Otherwise calls advance and refreshes current_char. EOF
without a trailing newline still returns 1 - end of source ends the
comment.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip COBOL comment (asterisk in column 7 or inline)

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Skip until end of line
    While current_char is not equal to 0:
        If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            proc advance from lexer
            Return 1
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token construction is the lexer's commitment point - every successful
token call corresponds to one parse-tree leaf. The lexeme (the actual
source text the token covers) is copied OUT of the source string into
a freshly allocated buffer so that the original source can be freed
or modified without affecting tokens already produced. Allocation
failure mid-construction must free the partial token; otherwise we leak
the 32-byte token record. Zero-length tokens (start_pos == end_pos)
take the no-lexeme path, identical to create_simple_token's record.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte token record. Returns 0 on failure. Writes type at
offset 0, line (lexer offset 24) at token offset 16, column (lexer
offset 32) at token offset 24. Computes lexeme_len = end_pos - start_pos.
If lexeme_len > 0: allocates lexeme_len+1 bytes; on failure frees the
token and returns 0. Loops i in 0..lexeme_len-1 copying byte-by-byte
via string_char_at(source, start_pos+i) and memory_set_byte(lexeme, i,
char). Writes null terminator at lexeme[lexeme_len], stores the lexeme
pointer at token offset 8. Otherwise (zero-length): writes 0 at offset
8. Returns the token handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes lexer as Integer, type as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token with lexeme from source range

    Let token_size be 32  Note: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, type

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Note: Extract lexeme from source
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let lexeme_len be end_pos minus start_pos

    If lexeme_len is greater than 0:
        Let arena be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
        Let lexeme be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_len plus 1

        If lexeme is equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with token
            Return 0
        End If

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than lexeme_len:
            Let char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, start_pos plus i
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with lexeme, i, char
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with lexeme, lexeme_len, 0  Note: null terminator

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme

    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, 0
    End If

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Optimised constructor for fixed-shape tokens whose meaning is fully
determined by their type constant: punctuation (period, comma,
parentheses), structural markers, and operator tokens. Skipping the
lexeme allocation reduces both heap churn and downstream lookup cost
- parsers that see lexeme==0 know to use the type constant directly
for matching rather than string-comparing the lexeme. Source position
is still recorded so error messages can point at the correct column.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 32-byte token record. Returns 0 on failure. Writes type
at offset 0, 0 at offset 8 (no lexeme). Reads line (lexer offset 24)
and column (lexer offset 32), writing them at token offsets 16 and 24.
Returns the token handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_simple_token" takes lexer as Integer, type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token without lexeme (for single-character tokens)

    Let token_size be 32
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, 0  Note: no lexeme

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85 numeric literals are pleasantly simple: an optional sign
(`+` or `-`), an integer part, an optional decimal point and fractional
part. There is NO scientific notation in standard COBOL (extensions
add it but bootstrap COBOL targets the standard), no hex/octal/binary
prefixes, no underscore digit separators. The lexer eats the longest
matching sequence and produces a TOKEN_NUMBER whose lexeme is the
verbatim source text - downstream typing (PIC clause) determines how
to interpret it (integer vs decimal vs binary-coded-decimal).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures position (offset 8) as start_pos and current_char (offset 40).
If current_char equals 43 ('+') or 45 ('-'), advances and refreshes
current_char (only one sign allowed). Enters digit loop: while
current_char != 0, calls is_digit; if returns 0 control falls through
the inner If (the Note: comments mark the break path used by Runa's
codegen). Advances on each digit. If current_char equals 46 ('.'),
advances and repeats the digit loop for the fractional part. Captures
end_pos (offset 8 again) and calls create_token(lexer, TOKEN_NUMBER,
start_pos, end_pos).
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize numeric literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Handle optional sign
    If current_char is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End If

    Note: Read integer part
    While current_char is not equal to 0:
        Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit from current_char
        If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
            Note: Break
            If current_char is greater than 0:
                Note: Continue after loop
            End If
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End While

    Note: Handle decimal point
    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

        Note: Read fractional part
        While current_char is not equal to 0:
            Set is_digit_result to proc is_digit from current_char
            If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
                Note: Break
                If current_char is greater than 0:
                    Note: Continue after loop
                End If
            End If

            proc advance from lexer
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
        End While
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let token be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_NUMBER, start_pos, end_pos

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL string literals accept either single quotes (`'TEXT'`) or double
quotes (`"TEXT"`); the opening quote determines the closing-quote
character for this literal (you cannot mix). The standard escape for
an embedded quote is the doubled-quote convention (`'It''s'` =
`It's`), no backslash escapes - that's a deliberate design choice
from COBOL's punched-card heritage where backslash wasn't widely
available. Unterminated strings (EOF before close quote) produce
TOKEN_ERROR_TOKEN rather than failing silently, letting the parser
report a precise diagnostic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures start_pos and current_char (the opening quote, stored as
quote_char so the doubled-escape test can use it). Calls advance to
skip the opening quote. Loop until EOF: if current_char equals
quote_char, advances and peeks the next character; if next_char equals
quote_char too (doubled escape), advances and continues the loop; else
emits TOKEN_STRING with create_token(lexer, TOKEN_STRING, start_pos,
end_pos) where end_pos is the post-close-quote position. Non-quote
characters are simply advanced over. EOF exit produces
TOKEN_ERROR_TOKEN at the partial range.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize string literal

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let quote_char be current_char

    proc advance from lexer  Note: Skip opening quote
    Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While current_char is not equal to 0:
        If current_char is equal to quote_char:
            proc advance from lexer
            Let next_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Note: Check for escaped quote (double quote)
            If next_char is equal to quote_char:
                proc advance from lexer
                Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Otherwise:
                Note: End of string
                Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let token be proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_STRING, start_pos, end_pos
                Return token
            End If

        Otherwise:
            proc advance from lexer
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
        End If
    End While

    Note: Unterminated string error
    Set end_pos to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Set token to proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_ERROR_TOKEN, start_pos, end_pos

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Keyword Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two-stage tokenisation: first scan the longest is_alphanumeric run
starting from current position (caller has already verified the first
character is is_alpha), then test the resulting text against the
keyword table. If it matches a keyword, emit that specific TOKEN_*;
otherwise emit TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. Doing the keyword lookup HERE rather
than in the parser means the parser sees structurally pre-classified
tokens, which simplifies the grammar dramatically (no "is this token
the IDENTIFIER 'DATA' or the keyword DATA?" ambiguity).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures start_pos (offset 8) and current_char (offset 40). Loops:
calls is_alphanumeric on current_char; advances on match, breaks
otherwise. Captures end_pos. Calls match_keyword(lexer, start_pos,
end_pos); if returns non-zero (a keyword TOKEN_* constant), creates
and returns a keyword token via create_token. Otherwise creates and
returns TOKEN_IDENTIFIER via create_token.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize identifier or keyword

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let start_pos be position
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While current_char is not equal to 0:
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric from current_char
        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            Note: Break
            If current_char is greater than 0:
                Note: Continue after loop
            End If
        End If

        proc advance from lexer
        Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let token_type be proc match_keyword with lexer, start_pos, end_pos

    If token_type is not equal to 0:
        Let token be proc create_token with lexer, token_type, start_pos, end_pos
        Return token
    End If

    Set token to proc create_token with lexer, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, start_pos, end_pos

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85 has 400+ reserved words; checking each one with a naive linear
loop would do ~400 string comparisons per identifier. We first-letter-
bucket: compute the upper-case form of the identifier's first byte
once, then only test keywords starting with that letter. This reduces
the average comparison count by ~25x for English keyword frequency.
Case-insensitivity is intrinsic to COBOL - `Data`, `DATA`, `data`, `DaTa`
all reference the same keyword - so we upper-case the first char (and
the per-keyword matcher upper-cases the rest) before comparing.
Returning 0 (not a keyword) lets tokenize_identifier fall through to
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER without an explicit error path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source pointer (lexer offset 0). Computes len = end_pos -
start_pos. Reads first_char at source+start_pos, calls
to_upper(first_char) -> first_upper. Branches on first_upper against
ASCII codepoints: 68 ('D') -> tests DATA, DIVISION, DISPLAY, DIVIDE,
DELETE via match_keyword_exact(source, start_pos, len, "DATA"); each
match returns the corresponding TOKEN_* constant. Similar branches
for 73 ('I'), 80 ('P'), 77 ('M'), ... covering all keyword
introducer letters. Falls through to Return 0 for unknown first
letters or no matches.
@End Implementation

Process called "match_keyword" takes lexer as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Match identifier against COBOL keywords

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let len be end_pos minus start_pos

    Note: Check first character for optimization
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, start_pos
    Let first_upper be proc to_upper from first_char

    Note: Division keywords
    If first_upper is equal to 68:  Note: 'D'
        Let match be proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "DATA"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DATA
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "DIVISION"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DIVISION
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "DISPLAY"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DISPLAY
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "DIVIDE"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DIVIDE
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "DELETE"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DELETE
        End If
    End If

    If first_upper is equal to 73:  Note: 'I'
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "IDENTIFICATION"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IDENTIFICATION
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "IF"
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IF
        End If
        Set match to proc match_keyword_exact with source, start_pos, len, "INTO"
